name: 3-hydroxybenzonitrile
Reason: The compound 3-hydroxybenzonitrile includes a phenol group and a nitrile group attached to the benzene ring. Starting with benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius, each substituent will affect the melting point. A rough additive effect of approximately +70 for the hydroxyl group can be considered. The nitrile group has a dipole and can engage in dipole-dipole interactions, further raising the melting point, though not as strongly as the hydroxyl group. For the nitrile group, we will estimate an additive effect of +20. Therefore, the cumulative effect of both functional groups is considered to be +90 degrees Celsius.
